about.summary: Bayesian analysis used here to answer the question: "when looking at resampling results, are the differences between models 'real'?" To answer this, a model can be created were the performance statistic is the resampling statistics (e.g. accuracy or RMSE). These values are explained by the model types. In doing this, we can get parameter estimates for each model's affect on performance and make statistical (and practical) comparisons between models. The methods included here are similar to Benavoli et al (2017) <http://jmlr.org/papers/v18/16-305.html>.

name: r-tidyposterior
raw_meta_yaml:
{% set version = "1.0.2" %}
{% set posix = 'm2-' if win else '' %}

package:
  name: r-tidyposterior
  version: {{ version|replace("-", "_") }}

source:
  url:
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/tidyposterior_{{ version }}.tar.gz
    - {{ cran_mirror }}/src/contrib/Archive/tidyposterior/tidyposterior_{{ version }}.tar.gz
  sha256: 0400b009939d2d527e1803f192d31ed8ffdbcc890a5931675359230cb873b2e1

build:
  number: 1
  noarch: generic
  rpaths:
    - lib/R/lib/
    - lib/

requirements:
  build:
    - {{ posix }}zip               # [win]
  host:
    - r-base
    - r-dplyr >1.0.0
    - r-generics
    - r-ggplot2
    - r-purrr
    - r-rlang
    - r-rsample >=0.0.2
    - r-rstanarm >=2.21.1
    - r-tibble
    - r-tidyr >=0.7.1
    - r-tune >=0.1.2.9000
    - r-vctrs >=0.3.0
    - r-workflowsets
  run:
    - r-base
    - r-dplyr >1.0.0
    - r-generics
    - r-ggplot2
    - r-purrr
    - r-rlang
    - r-rsample >=0.0.2
    - r-rstanarm >=2.21.1
    - r-tibble
    - r-tidyr >=0.7.1
    - r-tune >=0.1.2.9000
    - r-vctrs >=0.3.0
    - r-workflowsets

test:
  commands:
    - $R -e "library('tidyposterior')"           # [not win]
    - "\"%R%\" -e \"library('tidyposterior')\""  # [win]

about:
  home: https://tidymodels.github.io/tidyposterior
  license: MIT
  summary: "Bayesian analysis used here to answer the question: \"when looking at resampling results, are the differences between models 'real'?\" To answer this, a model can be created were the performance statistic is the resampling statistics (e.g. accuracy or RMSE). These values are explained by the model types. In doing
    this, we can get parameter estimates for each model's affect on performance and make statistical (and practical) comparisons between models. The methods included here are similar to Benavoli et al (2017) <http://jmlr.org/papers/v18/16-305.html>."
  license_family: MIT
  license_file:
    - {{ environ["PREFIX"] }}/lib/R/share/licenses/MIT
    - LICENSE

extra:
  recipe-maintainers:
    - conda-forge/r

In doing this, we can get parameter estimates for each model's affect on performance and make statistical (and practical) comparisons between models. The methods included here are similar to Benavoli et al (2017) <http://jmlr.org/papers/v18/16-305.html>.
